    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I want to make sure my students don't walk away thinking that the \"judicial activism\" argument is some kind of valid legal theory when it's really just an excuse to roll back rights. How can I frame the lesson so they see the substantive due process side as the necessary way to protect people from the \"tyranny of the majority\" that these critics talk about?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To counter the \"tyranny of the majority,\" you can frame substantive due process as the essential bulwark against democratic majoritarianism. It recognizes that some rights are so fundamental—like bodily autonomy or freedom of conscience—that they cannot be voted away by a simple majority. Therefore, the judiciary must act as a guardian of these inalienable rights, preventing the majority from legislating away the basic liberties of the minority. This protection of the individual against the collective is the core, necessary function of this doctrine.",
      "source": "target",
